===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=读}}
“To say aloud, to tell” (''{{w|Shijing}}'') > “to recite” > “to read”.

Cognate with {{cog|bo|ཀློག||to read; to recite}}. {{zh-ref|Starostin}} sets up {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*k-lok||to recite; to give notice}} for this, and also includes {{cog|my|လျှောက်||to tell; to ask; to petition; word-for-word translation; indiscriminately}} and {{cog|lus|thlûk||accent, tone, intonation}}. Related to {{och-l|讟|resentment, slander < to grumble; complaint}}.

STEDT provisionally sets up {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-g-(l/r)əwk||to read}}, relating it to {{och-l|牘|tablet}}.

{{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} argues that “read” cannot be the primary meaning, since existence of the concept “to read” before the invention of writing is questionable. There was likely no writing at the time of the split between Chinese and other Sino-Tibetan languages, therefore the Tibetan word may represent a borrowing from Chinese.

